    // FAQ
    'faq.title': 'Frequently Asked Questions',
    'faq.q1': 'When should I start tax planning?',
    'faq.a1': 'Tax planning must begin before any document is signed, ideally at negotiation stage. The applicable Purchase Tax rate depends on your residency status, whether this is your first property, and timing relative to any Aliyah. Getting this wrong is expensive and sometimes irreversible.',
    'faq.q2': 'How are buyer funds protected during the transaction?',
    'faq.a2': 'Buyer funds are released to the seller in stages, each tied to specific legal milestones. At each stage, a security interest (Hearat Azhara) is registered at the Land Registry in the buyer\'s favour. This ensures limited financial exposure if the transaction does not complete.',
    'faq.q3': 'Can I purchase property before making Aliyah?',
    'faq.a3': 'Yes. Non residents can purchase property in Israel. The more important question is the timing relative to your Aliyah date, as this affects Purchase Tax eligibility. In some cases purchasing before Aliyah preserves certain benefits. This analysis should be done before any commitment.',
    'faq.q4': 'Can I pay Israeli purchase tax in foreign currency?',
    'faq.a4': 'No. Purchase Tax payments to the Israeli Tax Authority are made in New Israeli Shekels. For clients transferring funds from abroad, this requires coordinating currency conversion, timing the transfer to limit exchange rate exposure, and ensuring the receiving Israeli bank accepts the funds. We manage this process as part of the transaction.',
    'faq.q5': 'Will the Israeli bank automatically accept my transfer?',
    'faq.a5': 'No. Israeli banks operate under strict anti money laundering requirements. An international transfer without prior documentation establishing the source of funds and purpose is likely to be held or returned. Preparing documentation in advance and coordinating with the bank before transferring is standard practice.',
    'faq.q6': 'When do I become a tax resident of Israel?',
    'faq.a6': 'Israeli tax residency is determined by the centre of life test, a factual assessment that includes physical presence of over 183 days in a tax year, as well as the location of your economic and personal ties. The consequences are significant and affect reporting obligations on worldwide income.',
    'faq.q7': 'Is a foreign will valid in Israel?',
    'faq.a7': 'A foreign will can be recognised in Israel but must go through a probate process including expert opinions on the relevant foreign law. This adds time and cost. The more reliable approach is to draft a separate Israeli will addressing Israeli assets, coordinated with your foreign will to avoid conflicts.',
    'faq.q8': 'Can I appoint an estate administrator residing outside Israel?',
    'faq.a8': 'Yes, though Israeli courts may require additional steps including guarantees before appointing a non resident administrator. The practical implications depend on the estate composition and complexity. We advise on executor selection with attention to the realistic demands of the role.',
    'faq.q9': 'What is the difference between an inheritance order and a probate order?',
    'faq.a9': 'A Probate Order (Kiyum Tzava\'a) confirms the validity of a will and authorises its execution. An Inheritance Order (Tzav Yerusha) is issued when no valid will exists, distributing the estate according to Israel\'s Succession Law. In cross border estates, coordination between jurisdictions is essential.',

